** "Every breath you take is mercy from me"
------------------------------------------------------------

Hold on; it turns out I'm not done thinking about Black Panther (https://k=
ottke.org/18/02/a-short-melancholy-review-of-black-panther) . (It's still=
 the biggest movie going=2C and one of the biggest of all time=2C so we ca=
n all be forgiven.) I saw it again=2C and I'm still convinced the key line=
 in the film is T'Challa's "every breath you take is mercy from me" =E2=80=
=94 spoken to Klaw (but not just to Klaw; it's really T'Challa's attitude=
 towards the entire world).

I also happen to know that this line is a lift from the comics=2C specific=
ally New Avengers vol. 3=2C no. 22=2C written by Jonathan Hickman. (Consid=
er New Avengers added to the recommended comics reading list for Black Pan=
ther (https://kottke.org/18/02/black-panther-a-suggested-comics-reading-li=
st) .) There=2C T'Challa says it to Namor=2C whom he's also intent on kill=
ing in retribution for murdering Wakandans. And there=2C the line conclude=
s=2C "... And I'm all out."

New Avengers 22=2C art by Kev Walker

It seems important that Black Panther is a superhero who is willing to kil=
l but prefers not to. Usually=2C superheroes are either killing people alm=
ost all the time (Logan=2C Deadpool=2C etc.)=2C or they've sworn never to=
 kill anyone (Batman=2C Spider-Man=2C etc.). Wonder Woman is one of the on=
ly other heroes who's ready and willing to use deadly force in extraordina=
ry circumstances=2C but is generally bent on saving people rather than kil=
ling them.

Part of what this does is it makes Black Panther's mercy mean something. H=
e saves=2C and offers to save=2C people he has every reason to kill. He's=
 appalled by his father's lack of mercy =E2=80=94 not so much for killing=
 his own brother=2C but for abandoning his brother's son (and in a larger=
 sense=2C all of Wakanda's lost children). T'Challa is a man who will not=
 waste a single Wakandan=2C who would never give up a single Wakandan life=
=2E This is his strongest contrast with Killmonger/N'Jadaku=2C who treats ev=
ery Wakandan (in fact=2C every person=2C including the black people of the=
 diaspora he claims to champion) as totally disposable.

So what we get with T'Challa is a doctrine of radical mercy (https://longr=
eads.com/2018/02/22/how-black-panther-asks-us-to-examine-who-we-are-to-one=
-another/) . He could kill all his enemies. He doesn't. He saves them. And=
 more than once (https://www.gq.com/story/black-panther-and-the-search-for=
-home) =2C that saves him.


** In case you haven't had enough
------------------------------------------------------------

There's a terrific decade-old profile of BP director Ryan Coogle (https://=
kottke.org/18/02/profile-of-21-year-old-film-student-ryan-coogler) r when=
 he was still a film student. There's a trailer for Fahrenheit 451 (https:=
//kottke.org/18/02/fahrenheit-451) =2C with Creed/Black Panther star Micha=
el B. Jordan. And there's a closer look at the typeface (https://kottke.or=
g/18/02/the-cool-futuristic-typeface-from-the-black-panther-ending-credits=
) used in BP's closing credits. Ah; we covered the story=2C the filmmaker=
=2C actors=2C and design. That works out quite neatly.


** I'm only here for the fonts
------------------------------------------------------------

I think you mean typefaces=2C but I got you. There are a full eight in use=
 on the iconic Huy Fong sriracha hot sauce label (https://kottke.org/18/02=
/all-the-typefaces-used-on-the-iconic-huy-fong-sriracha-label) =2C not cou=
nting the icon of the rooster. And if you just love crazy bits of juxtapos=
ed text=2C you want this Winter Olympics wrap-up written on a predictive t=
ext keyboard (https://kottke.org/18/02/a-winter-olympics-wrap-up-written-w=
ith-a-predictive-text-keyboard) . I for one cannot wait for speed torah-re=
ading to become a thing.


** You're probably doing this wrong
------------------------------------------------------------

You might know you should sneeze or cough into the inside of your elbow (h=
ttps://twitter.com/kottke/status/968540231178731521) =2C not your hands. Y=
ou should know to fact-check things before you share them on social media=
 (https://twitter.com/kottke/status/968155724810477568) =2C although I bet=
 we've all been embarrassed at least once. It would help if we used our sm=
art phones=2C um=2C smarter (https://kottke.org/18/02/were-all-addicted-to=
-the-smartphone-slot-machines-in-our-pockets) . But did you know that you'=
re probably bending over wrong (https://twitter.com/kottke/status/96852362=
3551193088) ? It's not at your waist=2C or even with your legs; you should=
 be bending with your hips. (In other words=2C you've got to stick your bu=
tt out.) This GIF shows you how:

Jenn Sherer/Spinefulness


